<h1>From Edmund Pendleton</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dr Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">July 3d 1769.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I have at Last found Leisure to peruse &amp; consider the papers you left with me for my Opinion on the nature of your Interest in your Fairfax Lands.</p>
<p>The deed of Settlement made by your Father on your brother Lawrence is long &amp; complicated occasioned chiefly by an Intention to provide against the contingincie of the Prince Wm Lands which were the Subject of that deed &amp; the Westmorland Lands Formerly Settled upon Augustine, From coming into the same
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0224">[224]</span>
hands by the death of one of your brothers without Issue, but as I take it For granted that your brother Augt. chose to keep the Westmorld Lands, and not to give them up &amp; take to the Prince William Lands as he had power to do upon the death of Lawrence without Issue, great part of that settlement is of little consequence, as to the Point you Now want to be Satisfied in.</p>
<p>The Prince William Lands then are limited to Lawrence in fee simple upon the Contingencies of his <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">leaving Issue at his death</span>: He takes notice of a daughter in his will &amp; if she survived him, your fathers Will has no operation upon the estate, but it must go according to the Will of yr brother Lawrence by which you take an estate tail, wth a remainder to your brother Augt. in fee simple; For tho the words of the devising clause would give you a fee, yet by a Subsequent one he directs that if you, Saml, John &amp; Charles or any of you, die <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">without Lawful Issue</span> such Land as was given you or any of you, should become the property of his brother Augustine &amp; his heirs forever, which changes your &amp; their Estates in all the Lands Claimed under his will into estates tail.</p>
<p>If indeed the daughter of Lawrence died before him, then as he left no Issue, The Land by the Settlement was to be subject to your fathers disposition and by his Will, you have a fee simple in the Prince William Lands, under the Remainder limited to you if Law[rence] died without Issue, since one of the contingencies upon wch you were to have a fee, has happened, that of your arriving to full age, altho you have no Issue. If this latter was the case, and you would choose to support yr fee simple, it might be proper to bring a Bill in Chancery to Perpetuate testimony to prove the fact of her dying before her father, as without testimony the presumption would be that she Survived, being named in his will; Nothing Further Occurs to me necessary to be mentioned.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0153-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0153-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> I am Sir Your mo. Obt humble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Edmd Pendleton</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0153-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0153-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0153-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>GWs half brother Lawrence Washington inherited the Mount Vernon tract from their father, Augustine Washington, in 1743. The Mount Vernon land, originally in Stafford County, fell into Prince William County when the county was formed from Stafford in 1730 and into Fairfax County in 1742 when Fairfax was formed from Prince William. At Lawrence Washingtons death in 1752, Mount Vernon went to his daughter Sarah (17501754). After
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0225">[225]</span>
Sarahs death, her mother, Ann Fairfax Washington Lee, who had a life right to the Mount Vernon property, leased the Mount Vernon property in 1754 to GW. At Ann Lees death in 1761, the estate passed to GW, Lawrence Washingtons oldest half brother. Lawrence Washingtons brother, Augustine Washington (17201762), received from their father the lands in Westmoreland County, including the old plantation and house where GW was born. Copies of Lawrence Washingtons will are in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Mount Vernon Ladies Association of the Union, Mount Vernon, Va. [[former abbreviation: ViMtV]] ]">ViMtvL</span>, and in the Fairfax County Will Book A (174252), 53942. A copy of the will of Augustine Washington (16941743), dated 11 April 1743, is in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>. Edmund Pendletons analysis of GWs rights under the two wills may have been the subject of the family meeting at Mount Vernon in the last week of February 1770 (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0203" class="document">GW to Charles Washington, 31 Jan. 1770</a>).</p>

</div>
